With dimensions just slightly larger than its .380ACP counterpart, the P938 packs six plus one rounds of 9mm into an all-metal frame. The cocked-and-locked single-action trigger gives the P938 unmatched accuracy in a pistol its size.

Fans of the 1911 will find the thumb safety, magazine release and slide stop lever in familiar places. An ambidextrous safety makes the P938 easy for left- and right-handed shooters. An extended seven-round magazine will be available separately.

Blackwood: A natural stainless steel slide and black hard coat anodized alloy frame are paired with Hogue Blackwood grips.

title: For Sale:  Discontinued .44 Magnum Marlin 1894C
postcontent:
I bought this handsome monster in 1991 but it sat forlorn in various closets till the week before last, when I finally took it to the range to finally fire it. A mere 20 rounds suggests this .44 magnum is just too much gun for me: there isn't much recoil but the very loud BOOM makes me flinch. And my bills were more than I'd expected so...

It's in great shape, with a cross-bar safety, a blued finish, the standard walnut stock, a hammer extension I see no need to remove, and a Micro-Groove barrel. (Wikipedia says "in the mid-1990s, Marlin changed the .357 and .44 barrels from 12-groove-or-more 'Micro-Groove' rifling to 6-groove 'Ballard' style rifling.") The only things wrong with this gun are that the folding leaf rear sight somehow broke off, and now there are a couple ugly but not fatal scratches on/near the sight base from where I tried and failed to install a replacement (see second photo). 

UPDATE: I went ahead and ordered another folding leaf rear sight from Midway; they say it shipped and will be here by July 7th, i.e. within a week. If somebody buys my rifle before then I'll mail it to you quickly to complete my end of the deal.

I won't be taking checks, credit cards, first-born sons, suckling goats, etc. And yes I'll consider a partial-value trade but still there has to be enough cash involved. 

You'll need to show me your valid KY driver's license or state ID, with a photocopy for my records; if you want I'll do the same. A CCDW would also help by establishing you're legally allowed to own a gun (but that's optional; I don't have one yet).

 The ARX160 is a rimfire version of the ARX100, Beretta’s celebrated .223 Rem tactical rifle. But aside from the caliber, this .22 LR rifle is virtually identical to the centerfire version as far as operations, controls, accessorization and customization options. A training rifle that will never let you down, the ARX160 is an extra-durable piece of gear that will satisfy even the most demanding tactical shooter.

Ambidextrous Controls

A serious training rifle should always mirror the “real thing” in the way its controls work. This is why the ARX160 features ambidextrous two-position safety, magazine release and cocking handle. With this rifle, you can easily train and shoot with either hand dominant and improve your skills without breaking the bank.

Limitless Accessorization, Customization Options

This training rifle is a great base for building the tactical system of your dreams. It comes out of the box with four Picatinny rails: on top, a full rail enables you to easily attach your favorite sighting or optics system, while on either side and on the bottom of the fore-end additional rails let you add other accessories such as tactical lighting. Other customization options include the telescopic folding stock: you can adjust the length of pull at the touch of a button, while the stock can be folded partially or all the way to accommodate most firing situations.


Durable, Easy to Shoot and Maintain

The ARX160 is built to be durable and super-tough, being constructed of superior steel and technopolymer. Its flip-up sights are just like those on the full-caliber rifle—super-light but rugged, and featuring a rear diopter for quick and accurate target acquisition. Maintenance is easy thanks to the simple way in which it comes apart and is reassembled without any tools. Whether you use it on its own as a rimfire tactical rifle, or as a training tool to improve your handling of the full-power counterpart, the ARX160 will always turn heads at the range and will never let you down.

title: For Sale:  Savage .308 Bolt Action/Precision work
postcontent:
Up for sale is a Savage Axis chambered in .308 Winchester.  It sits in the limited edition Moon Harvest camo stock and has probably seen less than 50 rounds. 

The major flaw with the Axis series is the wimpy flexible stock and stiff trigger. I have addressed these issues by reinforcing the fore-end of the stock with epoxy and aluminum flat bar.  There are a total of 6 aluminum reinforcements in the stock now.  The gaps around the trigger guard on the stock have been filled to eliminate side to side give as well.  The trigger has been set at 2.8 lbs and the trigger has been reshaped into a flat bar design that allows for more sensitivity in the finger tip-overall better trigger pulls leading to more accurate shots!  I have done what Savage should have done from the factory.  Way better performer now, will shoot 1 moa at 100 easily.  Custom gun work can cost a lot of money, save here with a great deal on a light weight bolt action that will deliver awesome performance for a budget.  

No scope is included. The rings and mount however is.
